05586nam a22007215i 9781501715648DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017156487 a10.1515/97815017156482doi  a(DE-B1597)577538  a(OCoLC)1302166505  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0360802bisacsh04a306.3/6209742231 aMosterman, Andrea C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSpaces of Enslavement :bA History of Slavery and Resistance in Dutch New York /cAndrea C. Mosterman. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2023  a1 online resource (246 p.) :b15 b&w halftones, 2 maps, 3 charts  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Netherland Institute Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: A Spatial Analysis of Slavery in Dutch New York -- t1. Enslaved Labor and the Settling of New Netherland -- t2. The Geography of Enslaved Life in New Netherland -- t3. Control and Resistance in the Public Space -- t4. Enslavement and the Dual Nature of the Home -- t5. Slavery and Social Power in Dutch Reformed Churches -- tConclusion: A More Benign System of Slavery? -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Spaces of Enslavement, Andrea C. Mosterman addresses the persistent myth that the colonial Dutch system of slavery was more humane. Investigating practices of enslavement in New Netherland and then in New York, Mosterman shows that these ways of racialized spatial control held much in common with the southern plantation societies.In the 1620s, Dutch colonial settlers brought slavery to the banks of the Hudson River and founded communities from New Amsterdam in the south to Beverwijck near the terminus of the navigable river. When Dutch power in North America collapsed and the colony came under English control in 1664, Dutch descendants continued to rely on enslaved labor. Until 1827, when slavery was abolished in New York State, slavery expanded in the region, with all free New Yorkers benefitting from that servitude. Mosterman describes how the movements of enslaved persons were controlled in homes and in public spaces such as workshops, courts, and churches. She addresses how enslaved people responded to regimes of control by escaping from or modifying these spaces so as to expand their activities within them. Through a close analysis of homes, churches, and public spaces, Mosterman shows that, over the course of the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries, the region's Dutch communities were engaged in a daily struggle with Black New Yorkers who found ways to claim freedom and resist oppression.Spaces of Enslavement writes a critical and overdue chapter on the place of slavery and resistance in the colony and young state of New York.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDutchzNew York (State)xHistoryy17th century. 0aDutchzNew York (State)xHistoryy18th century. 0aDutchzNew York (State)xHistoryy19th century. 0aSlaveryzNew York (State)xHistoryy17th century. 0aSlaveryzNew York (State)xHistoryy18th century. 0aSlaveryzNew York (State)xHistoryy19th century. 0aSlaveszNew York (State)xSocial conditionsy17th century. 0aSlaveszNew York (State)xSocial conditionsy18th century. 0aSlaveszNew York (State)xSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aSpatial behaviorxSocial aspectszNew York (State)xHistoryy17th century. 0aSpatial behaviorxSocial aspectszNew York (State)xHistoryy18th century. 0aSpatial behaviorxSocial aspectszNew York (State)xHistoryy19th century. 4aAfrican-American Studies. 4aNew York History. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / Mid